WEBVTT

1
00:00:57.878 --> 00:00:59.152
[Banging]

2
00:01:02.238 --> 00:01:04.069
HENRY: What the fuck is that?

3
00:01:04.158 --> 00:01:05.273
Jimmy?

4
00:01:05.358 --> 00:01:07.588
TOMMY: What's up?
HENRY: Did I hit something?

5
00:01:07.678 --> 00:01:09.555
TOMMY: What the fuck is that?

6
00:01:10.598 --> 00:01:12.429
TOMMY: Maybe you got a flat?

7
00:01:13.598 --> 00:01:14.667
HENRY: No.

8
00:01:16.038 --> 00:01:18.871
TOMMY: What the fuck?
You better pull over and see.

9
00:01:18.958 --> 00:01:20.232
[Banging]

10
00:01:26.518 --> 00:01:28.236
[Banging continues]

11
00:01:44.038 --> 00:01:46.074
TOMMY: He's still alive. You piece of shit!

12
00:01:46.158 --> 00:01:47.113
Die. motherfucker!

13
00:01:47.198 --> 00:01:48.108
[Grunting]

14
00:01:48.198 --> 00:01:49.551
TOMMY: Look at me!

15
00:01:51.838 --> 00:01:53.556
[Multiple gunshots]

16
00:01:58.158 --> 00:02:01.992
HENRY: <i>As far back as I can remember.</i>
<i>I always wanted to be a gangster.</i>

17
00:02:02.078 --> 00:02:04.467
[Big band tune plays. background]

18
00:02:09.078 --> 00:02:11.467
<i>"I know I'd go from rags to riches"</i>

19
00:02:14.958 --> 00:02:17.233
<i>"If you would only say you care</i>

20
00:02:21.278 --> 00:02:23.712
<i>"And though my pocket may be empty</i>

21
00:02:27.278 --> 00:02:29.075
<i>"I'd be a millionaire</i>

22
00:02:33.078 --> 00:02:35.956
<i>"My clothes may still be torn and tattered"</i>

23
00:02:40.198 --> 00:02:41.426
HENRY: <i>To me...</i>

24
00:02:41.798 --> 00:02:45.791
<i>... being a gangster was better than</i>
<i>being president of the United States.</i>

25
00:02:48.998 --> 00:02:52.115
<i>Even before I went to the cabstand</i>
<i>for an after-school job...</i>

26
00:02:52.198 --> 00:02:54.473
<i>... I knew I wanted to be a part of them.</i>

27
00:02:54.558 --> 00:02:58.710
<i>It was there that I knew I belonged.</i>
<i>To me. it meant being somebody...</i>

28
00:02:58.918 --> 00:03:01.193
<i>... in a neighborhood full of nobodies.</i>

29
00:03:01.318 --> 00:03:04.708
<i>They weren't like anybody else.</i>
<i>They did whatever they wanted.</i>

30
00:03:04.878 --> 00:03:08.154
<i>They parked in front of hydrants</i>
<i>and never got a ticket.</i>

31
00:03:08.238 --> 00:03:10.354
<i>When they played cards all night...</i>

32
00:03:10.438 --> 00:03:12.474
<i>... nobody ever called the cops.</i>

33
00:03:12.558 --> 00:03:15.914
[Big band tune continues]
<i>"Must I forever be a beggar</i>

34
00:03:19.078 --> 00:03:21.831
<i>"Whose golden dreams will not come true"</i>

35
00:03:24.158 --> 00:03:26.228
TUDDY: Tony Stacks. How are you?

36
00:03:27.238 --> 00:03:28.671
HENRY: <i>Tuddy Cicero.</i>

37
00:03:28.958 --> 00:03:31.188
TONY: Could this be the Canarsie Kid?

38
00:03:34.158 --> 00:03:35.352
HENRY: <i>Tuddy.</i>

39
00:03:36.198 --> 00:03:39.429
<i>Tuddy ran the cabstand</i>
<i>and the Bella Vista Pizzeria...</i>

40
00:03:39.558 --> 00:03:44.234
<i>... and other places for his brother. Paul.</i>
<i>who was the boss of the neighborhood.</i>

41
00:03:44.318 --> 00:03:46.354
[Chattering and chuckling]

42
00:03:48.198 --> 00:03:50.473
<i>Paulie might have moved slow...</i>

43
00:03:52.958 --> 00:03:56.792
<i>... but it was only because Paulie didn't</i>
<i>have to move for anybody.</i>

44
00:04:00.758 --> 00:04:02.953
TONY: It's your fault.
RONNIE: You started it!

45
00:04:03.038 --> 00:04:04.869
TONY: I started it? It's your fault.

46
00:04:05.478 --> 00:04:07.753
HENRY: <i>At first my parents loved</i>
<i>that I found a job...</i>

47
00:04:07.838 --> 00:04:09.908
<i>... across the street from the house.</i>

48
00:04:10.278 --> 00:04:13.907
<i>My father. who was Irish.</i>
<i>was sent to work at the age of 11.</i>

49
00:04:14.118 --> 00:04:16.188
<i>He liked that I got myself a job.</i>

50
00:04:16.318 --> 00:04:19.754
<i>He always used to say</i>
<i>that American kids were spoiled lazy.</i>

51
00:04:25.918 --> 00:04:28.068
HENRY'S MOTHER:
Henry! Watch how you cross!

52
00:04:28.158 --> 00:04:29.591
Bring back milk!

53
00:04:29.838 --> 00:04:32.716
HENRY: <i>My mother was happy</i>
<i>after she found out the Ciceros...</i>

54
00:04:32.798 --> 00:04:36.347
<i>... came from the same part of Sicily</i>
<i>as she did. To my mother...</i>

55
00:04:36.638 --> 00:04:39.106
<i>... that was the answer to all her prayers.</i>

56
00:04:40.478 --> 00:04:42.514
<i>I was the luckiest kid in the world.</i>

57
00:04:42.598 --> 00:04:44.828
<i>I could go anywhere. do anything.</i>

58
00:04:45.598 --> 00:04:48.351
<i>I knew everybody. and everybody knew me.</i>

59
00:04:48.798 --> 00:04:52.916
<i>Wiseguys would pull up and Tuddy</i>
<i>would let me park their Cadillacs.</i>

60
00:04:53.358 --> 00:04:56.873
<i>Here I am. this little kid.</i>
<i>I can't even see over the steering wheel...</i>

61
00:04:56.958 --> 00:04:58.914
<i>... and I'm parking Cadillacs.</i>

62
00:05:02.278 --> 00:05:04.189
<i>But. it wasn't too long...</i>

63
00:05:04.358 --> 00:05:08.510
<i>... before my parents changed</i>
<i>their minds about my job at the cabstand.</i>

64
00:05:09.798 --> 00:05:13.268
<i>For them. it was supposed to be</i>
<i>a part-time job. But for me...</i>

65
00:05:13.518 --> 00:05:15.270
<i>... it was definitely full time.</i>

66
00:05:15.358 --> 00:05:17.155
<i>That's all I wanted to do.</i>

67
00:05:17.438 --> 00:05:21.397
<i>People like my father could never</i>
<i>understand. but I was a part of something.</i>

68
00:05:21.478 --> 00:05:24.197
<i>I belonged. I was treated like a grown-up.</i>

69
00:05:24.478 --> 00:05:25.957
TUDDY: Tell him 519.

70
00:05:26.598 --> 00:05:28.873
HENRY: <i>Every day I was learning to score.</i>

71
00:05:28.958 --> 00:05:32.553
<i>A dollar here. a dollar there.</i>
<i>I was living in a fantasy.</i>

72
00:05:35.118 --> 00:05:36.949
Did you have a good day at school?

73
00:05:37.038 --> 00:05:39.268
HENRY: <i>My father was always pissed off.</i>

74
00:05:39.358 --> 00:05:42.714
<i>Pissed that he made such lousy money.</i>
<i>that my brother Michael...</i>

75
00:05:42.798 --> 00:05:44.277
<i>... was in a wheelchair.</i>

76
00:05:44.358 --> 00:05:48.192
<i>He was pissed that there were seven of us</i>
<i>living in such a tiny house.</i>

77
00:05:48.558 --> 00:05:50.071
Tell me about this.

78
00:05:50.598 --> 00:05:53.066
HENRY'S FATHER: It's a letter from school.

79
00:05:53.158 --> 00:05:55.592
It says you haven't been there in months.

80
00:05:57.118 --> 00:05:58.392
In months!

81
00:05:58.518 --> 00:05:59.792
[Henry's mother screams]

82
00:05:59.878 --> 00:06:01.311
You're a bum!

83
00:06:01.758 --> 00:06:03.510
Want to grow up to be a bum?

84
00:06:03.598 --> 00:06:04.826
[Slapping and screaming]

85
00:06:04.918 --> 00:06:07.068
HENRY: <i>After a while.</i>
<i>he was mostly pissed...</i>

86
00:06:07.158 --> 00:06:09.228
<i>... because I hung around the cabstand.</i>

87
00:06:09.318 --> 00:06:11.195
<i>He knew what went on there.</i>

88
00:06:11.398 --> 00:06:15.914
<i>Every once in a while I'd have to take</i>
<i>a beating. But by then. I didn't care.</i>

89
00:06:16.158 --> 00:06:17.750
<i>The way I saw it...</i>

90
00:06:18.118 --> 00:06:20.632
<i>... everybody takes a beating sometime.</i>

91
00:06:21.678 --> 00:06:23.316
I can't make any more deliveries.

92
00:06:23.398 --> 00:06:25.514
What? You'll fuck everything up.

93
00:06:25.598 --> 00:06:27.668
My dad says he'll kill me. Look.

94
00:06:27.838 --> 00:06:29.032
Come with me.

95
00:06:29.158 --> 00:06:31.228
TONY: Is that him there?
HENRY: No.

96
00:06:31.758 --> 00:06:33.749
RONNIE: How about him?
HENRY: No.

97
00:06:35.238 --> 00:06:37.547
HENRY: That's the guy...
RONNIE: Get him.

98
00:06:38.878 --> 00:06:40.152
TONY: Excuse me.

99
00:06:41.158 --> 00:06:44.116
TONY: Scumbag.
WISEGUY: Come here. you piece of shit.

100
00:06:48.078 --> 00:06:49.147
[Smashing]

101
00:06:51.638 --> 00:06:53.151
TUDDY: Know this kid?
MAILMAN: Yeah.

102
00:06:53.238 --> 00:06:55.069
TUDDY: Know where he lives?
MAILMAN: Yeah.

103
00:06:55.158 --> 00:06:57.513
TUDDY: You deliver mail to his house?
MAILMAN: Yeah.

104
00:06:57.598 --> 00:07:01.227
TUDDY: From now on. any letter from
school to his house comes directly here.

105
00:07:01.318 --> 00:07:02.546
Understand?

106
00:07:02.718 --> 00:07:05.835
TUDDY: Another letter from school
goes to that kid's house...

107
00:07:05.918 --> 00:07:07.909
...in the oven you'll go. head first.

108
00:07:07.998 --> 00:07:12.276
HENRY: <i>That was it. No more letters from</i>
<i>truant officers. No letters from school.</i>

109
00:07:12.358 --> 00:07:14.314
<i>In fact. no more letters from anybody.</i>

110
00:07:14.398 --> 00:07:17.037
<i>After a few weeks. my mother went</i>
<i>to the post office to complain.</i>

111
00:07:18.318 --> 00:07:20.229
<i>How could I go to school after that...</i>

112
00:07:20.318 --> 00:07:23.913
<i>... and pledge allegiance and sit through</i>
<i>good government bullshit?</i>

113
00:07:24.198 --> 00:07:25.677
[Rain pelting]

114
00:07:26.958 --> 00:07:30.428
HENRY: <i>Paulie hated phones.</i>
<i>He wouldn't have one in his house.</i>

115
00:07:30.598 --> 00:07:32.907
TUDDY: Mickey called.
Want me to call him back?

116
00:07:32.998 --> 00:07:34.636
PAUL: All right. make the call.

117
00:07:34.718 --> 00:07:39.189
HENRY: <i>He got all his calls second hand.</i>
<i>Then you'd have to call the people back.</i>

118
00:07:39.438 --> 00:07:41.827
TUDDY: Got a nickel?
Get him on the phone.

119
00:07:42.558 --> 00:07:47.188
HENRY: <i>There were guys. that's all they</i>
<i>did all day. was take care of Paulie's calls.</i>

120
00:07:53.678 --> 00:07:56.272
[Scattered conversation.
pop tune plays in background]

121
00:07:56.358 --> 00:07:58.633
<i>For a guy who moved all day long...</i>

122
00:07:58.878 --> 00:08:01.711
<i>... Paulie didn't talk to six people.</i>
<i>With union problems...</i>

123
00:08:01.798 --> 00:08:03.675
<i>... or a beef in the numbers...</i>

124
00:08:03.918 --> 00:08:07.035
<i>... only the top guys spoke</i>
<i>with Paulie about the problem.</i>

125
00:08:07.278 --> 00:08:10.588
<i>Everything was one-on-one.</i>
<i>Paulie hated conferences.</i>

126
00:08:10.918 --> 00:08:13.512
<i>He didn't want anybody</i>
<i>hearing what he said...</i>

127
00:08:13.598 --> 00:08:16.510
<i>... or anyone listening to</i>
<i>what he was being told.</i>

128
00:08:16.798 --> 00:08:20.950
<i>Hundreds of guys depended on him. and</i>
<i>he got a piece of everything they made.</i>

129
00:08:21.118 --> 00:08:25.430
<i>It was a tribute. like in the old country.</i>
<i>except they were doing it in America.</i>

130
00:08:25.638 --> 00:08:29.756
<i>All they got from Paulie was protection</i>
<i>from the guys trying to rip them off.</i>

131
00:08:29.958 --> 00:08:33.917
<i>That's what it's all about. That's</i>
<i>what the FBI could never understand.</i>

132
00:08:34.158 --> 00:08:36.547
<i>What Paulie and the Organization does...</i>

133
00:08:36.678 --> 00:08:40.307
<i>... is protect people who can't</i>
<i>go to the cops. That's it.</i>

134
00:08:41.678 --> 00:08:44.795
<i>They're like the police department</i>
<i>for wiseguys.</i>

135
00:08:46.198 --> 00:08:48.348
[Smashing. glass shattering]

136
00:08:54.158 --> 00:08:58.151
HENRY: <i>People looked at me differently.</i>
<i>and they knew I was with somebody.</i>

137
00:08:58.398 --> 00:09:02.596
<i>I didn't have to wait in line at the bakery</i>
<i>on Sunday morning for fresh bread.</i>

138
00:09:02.718 --> 00:09:06.950
<i>The owner knew who I was with. and no</i>
<i>matter how many people were waiting...</i>

139
00:09:07.038 --> 00:09:08.915
<i>... I was taken care of first.</i>

140
00:09:09.518 --> 00:09:13.431
<i>Our neighbors stopped parking in</i>
<i>our driveway. even though we had no car.</i>

141
00:09:13.598 --> 00:09:14.633
HENRY: <i>At 13...</i>

142
00:09:14.718 --> 00:09:19.030
<i>... I was making more money than most</i>
<i>of the grown-ups in the neighborhood.</i>

143
00:09:19.278 --> 00:09:20.711
<i>I had it all.</i>

144
00:09:23.078 --> 00:09:24.796
[Roaring explosion]

145
00:09:28.878 --> 00:09:30.231
HENRY: <i>One day...</i>

146
00:09:30.318 --> 00:09:34.709
<i>One day. some neighborhood kids carried</i>
<i>my mother's groceries all the way home.</i>

147
00:09:34.958 --> 00:09:36.232
<i>You know why?</i>

148
00:09:37.038 --> 00:09:38.869
<i>It was out of respect.</i>

149
00:09:40.558 --> 00:09:41.911
What do you think?

150
00:09:43.998 --> 00:09:45.829
HENRY: Aren't my shoes great?

151
00:09:47.198 --> 00:09:48.790
You look like a gangster.

152
00:09:48.878 --> 00:09:50.709
[Yells] They shot me. Help!

153
00:09:52.878 --> 00:09:54.675
TUDDY: Henry. shut the door.

154
00:09:55.598 --> 00:09:58.829
HENRY: <i>That was the first time</i>
<i>I had ever seen anyone shot.</i>

155
00:09:59.758 --> 00:10:01.874
Can't have that in here. Jesus Christ!

156
00:10:01.958 --> 00:10:03.914
TUDDY: I can't have that in this joint.

157
00:10:03.998 --> 00:10:06.637
HENRY: <i>I remember feeling bad</i>
<i>about the guy. but also...</i>

158
00:10:06.718 --> 00:10:08.595
<i>... feeling maybe Tuddy was right.</i>

159
00:10:08.678 --> 00:10:11.431
<i>I knew Paulie didn't want</i>
<i>anyone dying in the building.</i>

160
00:10:11.518 --> 00:10:15.113
You're a real jerk. You wasted
eight fucking aprons on this guy.

161
00:10:15.438 --> 00:10:18.475
What's wrong with you?
I got to toughen this kid up.

162
00:10:22.638 --> 00:10:25.027
[Upbeat pop tune plays. background]

163
00:10:37.358 --> 00:10:39.269
HENRY: <i>It was a glorious time.</i>

164
00:10:40.078 --> 00:10:42.672
<i>And wiseguys were all over the place.</i>

165
00:10:43.518 --> 00:10:46.237
<i>It was before Apalachin</i>
<i>and before Crazy Joe...</i>

166
00:10:46.478 --> 00:10:49.197
<i>... decided to take on</i>
<i>a boss and start a war.</i>

167
00:10:50.078 --> 00:10:51.909
<i>It was when I met the world.</i>

168
00:10:52.158 --> 00:10:54.797
<i>And it was when</i>
<i>I first met Jimmy Conway.</i>

169
00:10:55.998 --> 00:11:00.628
<i>He couldn't have been more than 28 or 29</i>
<i>at the time. but he was already a legend.</i>

170
00:11:01.278 --> 00:11:05.112
<i>He'd walk in the door and everybody</i>
<i>who worked the room just went wild.</i>

171
00:11:05.278 --> 00:11:07.917
<i>He'd give a doorman $100</i>
<i>just for opening the door.</i>

172
00:11:07.998 --> 00:11:11.593
<i>He'd give hundreds to the dealers</i>
<i>and the guys who ran the games.</i>

173
00:11:11.838 --> 00:11:14.716
<i>The bartender got $100 just</i>
<i>for keeping the ice cubes cold.</i>

174
00:11:14.798 --> 00:11:17.835
JIMMY: The Irishman is here
to take you Guineas' money.

175
00:11:20.478 --> 00:11:23.436
PAUL: Want a drink?
JIMMY: Give me a Seven and Seven.

176
00:11:30.118 --> 00:11:32.268
PAUL: I'd like you to meet the kid Henry.

177
00:11:32.358 --> 00:11:33.837
How you doin'?

178
00:11:36.038 --> 00:11:37.107
Thank you.

179
00:11:37.318 --> 00:11:38.467
Keep them coming.

180
00:11:38.558 --> 00:11:41.595
HENRY: <i>Jimmy was one of the most</i>
<i>feared guys in the city.</i>

181
00:11:41.678 --> 00:11:45.751
<i>He was first locked up at 11.</i>
<i>and doing hits for mob bosses at 16.</i>

182
00:11:46.398 --> 00:11:49.231
<i>Hits never bothered Jimmy.</i>
<i>It was business.</i>

183
00:11:49.598 --> 00:11:53.591
<i>But what Jimmy really loved to do...</i>
<i>what he really loved to do was steal.</i>

184
00:11:53.838 --> 00:11:55.749
<i>He actually enjoyed it.</i>

185
00:11:56.238 --> 00:12:00.072
<i>Jimmy was the kind of guy who rooted</i>
<i>for the bad guys in movies.</i>

186
00:12:00.718 --> 00:12:02.197
Give me your wallet.

187
00:12:05.118 --> 00:12:08.155
You might know who we are.
but we know who you are.

188
00:12:08.238 --> 00:12:10.798
HENRY: <i>He was one of the city's</i>
<i>biggest hijackers...</i>

189
00:12:10.878 --> 00:12:14.154
<i>... of booze. cigarettes. razor blades.</i>
<i>shrimp and lobsters.</i>

190
00:12:14.238 --> 00:12:15.910
<i>Shrimp and lobsters were best.</i>

191
00:12:15.998 --> 00:12:17.272
<i>They went fast.</i>

192
00:12:17.518 --> 00:12:21.113
<i>Almost all of them were gimmies.</i>
<i>They just gave it up. no problem.</i>

193
00:12:21.198 --> 00:12:22.790
<i>They called him Jimmy the Gent.</i>

194
00:12:22.878 --> 00:12:24.072
JIMMY: Help the lady.

195
00:12:24.158 --> 00:12:26.433
HENRY: <i>Drivers loved him.</i>
<i>They used to tip him off...</i>

196
00:12:26.518 --> 00:12:29.908
<i>... about the really good loads.</i>
<i>Of course. everybody got a piece.</i>

197
00:12:29.998 --> 00:12:32.990
SCHOOL GUARD:
Thanks. I'll be back for the rest later.

198
00:12:35.918 --> 00:12:37.271
Henry. come here.

199
00:12:38.158 --> 00:12:39.591
Say hello to Tommy.

200
00:12:40.238 --> 00:12:43.548
You're gonna be working together. okay?
Help him. Go ahead.

201
00:12:44.558 --> 00:12:46.549
Jimmy. you got anything good?

202
00:12:46.878 --> 00:12:50.791
HENRY: <i>When the cops assigned a whole</i>
<i>army to stop Jimmy. what did he do?</i>

203
00:12:52.078 --> 00:12:53.670
<i>He made them partners.</i>

204
00:12:53.918 --> 00:12:55.590
I'd complain. but who'd listen?

205
00:12:56.758 --> 00:12:59.352
HENRY: What do you need?
CIGARETTE BUYER 1: Two Luckys.

206
00:12:59.438 --> 00:13:02.032
TOMMY: Here you go. Henry.
HENRY: Thanks a lot.

